      "url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Four_Brown_Berets_leaders%2C_Fred_Lopez%2C_David_Sanchez_%2C_Carlos_Montes_and_Ralph_Ramirez_in_Los_Angeles%2C_Calif.%2C_1968_%28cropped%29.jpg/1920px-Four_Brown_Berets_leaders%2C_Fred_Lopez%2C_David_Sanchez_%2C_Carlos_Montes_and_Ralph_Ramirez_in_Los_Angeles%2C_Calif.%2C_1968_%28cropped%29.jpg",
      "caption": "Four Brown Berets leaders: Fred Lopez, David Sanchez, Carlos Montes, and Ralph Ramirez in Los Angeles, California, 1968. Photo Courtesy of the Los Angeles Times and the UCLA Library Digital Collections.",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The Brown Berets was a Chicano paramilitary organization that was part of the Chicano Movement and took inspiration from the Black Panthers. They were formed in Los Angeles and were most active between 1967 and 1972. TBB had chapters across the country, one of which was on San Antonio’s Westside. They fought for many different aspects of Chicano civil rights, but their main cause was fighting against police brutality, as well as educational reform."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Their members consisted mostly of Vietnam Veterans. Many Mexican Americans served in the Vietnam War, either by choice or by military draft, and faced brutal conditions during their service. When they returned to the United States, they still dealt with intense discrimination. This is what inspired many of them to use the skills they had learned in the military to create the Brown Berets and protect their communities."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Though the Brown Berets actively fought for civil rights, there were equality issues within the organization between men and women. Women were often discouraged from joining, and when they did, they were often relegated to more “feminine” tasks such as cleaning and clerical work. They were expected to defer to their male counterparts, an aspect of “Machismo,” a hyper-masculine ideology present in many Latino cultures that placed emphasis on the more negative aspects of masculinity, such as aggression and sexism. By joining the Brown Berets and participating in the same activities the men did, Montejano actively fought against this."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
